<activity xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="act-8a-1-1">
	<statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>f(x)=e^x</m> and <m>T_2(x) = c_0 + c_1 x + c_2 x^2</m>.  We seek numerical values for the constants <m>c_0</m>, <m>c_1</m>, and <m>c_2</m> so that <m>f(0)=T_2(0)</m>, <m>f'(0)=T_2'(0)</m>, and <m>f''(0)=T_2''(0)</m>.
		</p>
		<p>
			<ol marker="a.">
				<li>
				<p>
					Note that since <m>c_0</m>, <m>c_1</m>, and <m>c_2</m> are constants, if we take the derivative of the quadratic function <m>T_2</m> using the sum and constant multiple rules, it follows that <m>T_2'(x) = c_1 + 2 c_2 x</m>.  
				</p>

				<p>
					What is <m>T_2''(x)</m>?
				</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Recall that <m>f(x) = e^x</m>.  Determine <m>f'(x)</m> and <m>f''(x)</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Enter the formulas you've determined for <m>f(x)</m>, <m>f'(x)</m>, <m>f''(x)</m>, <m>T_2(x)</m>, <m>T_2'(x)</m>, and <m>T_2''(x)</m> in <xref ref="T-act-8a-1-1-formulas">Table</xref>.

						<table xml:id="T-act-8a-1-1-formulas">
						<title>Formulas for <m>f(x)</m> and <m>T_2(x)</m> and their derivatives.</title>
							<tabular top="none" bottom="none">
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f'(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2'(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
								</row>                
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f''(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2''(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
								</row>
							</tabular>
						</table>
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Next, observe that since <m>T_2(x) = c_0 + c_1 x + c_2 x^2</m>, it follows that <m>T_2(0) = c_0</m>.  Reason similarly to determine the values of <m>T_2'(0)</m> and <m>T_2''(0)</m>, as well as those of <m>f(0)</m>, <m>f'(0)</m>, and <m>f''(0)</m> and enter these 6 values appropriately in <xref ref="T-act-8a-1-1-values">Table</xref>.

						<table xml:id="T-act-8a-1-1-values">
						<title>Values of <m>f(x)</m> and <m>T_2(x)</m> and their derivatives at <m>x = 0</m>.</title>
							<tabular top="none" bottom="none">
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f'(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2'(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
								</row>                
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f''(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2''(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><fillin /></cell>
								</row>
							</tabular>
						</table>
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Now, recall that we want the function values, first derivative values, and second derivative values of <m>f</m> and <m>T_2</m> to match at <m>a = 0</m>.  What does <m>T_2(0) = f(0)</m> tell us about the value of <m>c_0</m>? What does <m>T_2'(0) = f'(0)</m> tell us about <m>c_1</m>? How can we also find <m>c_2</m>?  
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Having now determined the numerical values of <m>c_0</m>, <m>c_1</m>, and <m>c_2</m>, plot the function <m>T_2(x) = c_0 + c_1 x + c_2 x^2</m> along with <m>f(x)=e^x</m> and <m>T_1(x)=1+x</m> in <xref ref="F-8a-1-act-1">Figure</xref>.  What do you notice?  For about which values of <m>x</m> is <m>|f(x)-T_2(x)| \lt 0.1</m>?

						<figure xml:id="F-8a-1-act-1">
							<caption>The function <m>f(x)=e^x</m> and its tangent line <m>T_1(x)=1+x</m> near the point <m>(0,f(0))</m>.</caption>
							<image width="50%" source="images/8a_1_act_1" />
						</figure>
					</p>		
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>
		</statement>
		<hint>
			
		</hint>
		<answer>

		<p>
			<ol marker="a.">
				<li>
				<p>
					<m>T_2''(x) = 2c_2</m>.
				</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						<m>f'(x) = f''(x)= e^x</m>.  
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						<table xml:id="T-act-8a-1-1-ans">
						<title>Formulas and values for <m>f(x)</m> and <m>T_2(x)</m>.</title>
							<tabular top="none" bottom="none">
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>e^x</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>c_0 + c_1 x + c_2 x^2</m></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f'(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>e^x</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2'(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>c_1 + 2c_2 x</m></cell>
								</row>                
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f''(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>e^x</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2''(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>2c_2</m></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell></cell>
									<cell></cell>
									<cell></cell>
									<cell></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>1</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>c_0</m></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f'(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>1</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2'(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>c_1</m></cell>
								</row>                
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f''(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>1</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2''(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>2c_2</m></cell>
								</row>
							</tabular>
						</table>
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						See the bottom half of the table above.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						<m>c_0 = 1</m>; <m>c_1 = 1</m>; <m>c_2 = \frac{1}{2}</m>.  So, <m>T_2(x) = 1 + x + \frac{1}{2} x^2</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						<m>T_2(x)</m> is a better approximation to <m>f(x) = e^x</m> near <m>a = 0</m> than the tangent line; <m>|f(x)-T_2(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for approximately <m>-0.9 \lt x \lt 0.8</m>, and for any <m>x</m>-value in that interval, <m>|f(x)-T_2(x)| \lt |f(x)-T_1(x)|</m>. 
					</p>		
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>
			
		</answer>
		<solution>

		<p>
			Let <m>f(x)=e^x</m> and <m>T_2(x) = c_0 + c_1 x + c_2 x^2</m>.  
		</p>
		<p>
			<ol marker="a.">
				<li>
				<p>
					<m>T_2''(x) = 2c_2</m>.
				</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						<m>f'(x) = f''(x)= e^x</m>.  
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						<table xml:id="T-act-8a-1-1-soln">
						<title>Formulas and values for <m>f(x)</m> and <m>T_2(x)</m>.</title>
							<tabular top="none" bottom="none">
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>e^x</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>c_0 + c_1 x + c_2 x^2</m></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f'(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>e^x</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2'(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>c_1 + 2c_2 x</m></cell>
								</row>                
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f''(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>e^x</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2''(x)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>2c_2</m></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell></cell>
									<cell></cell>
									<cell></cell>
									<cell></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>1</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>c_0</m></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f'(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>1</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2'(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>c_1</m></cell>
								</row>                
								<row>
									<cell halign="right"><m>f''(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>1</m></cell>
									<cell halign="right"><m>T_2''(0)=</m></cell>
									<cell><m>2c_2</m></cell>
								</row>
							</tabular>
						</table>
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						See the bottom half of the table above.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						The condition that <m>T_2(0) = f(0)</m> tells us <m>c_0 = 1</m>.  Reasoning similarly, <m>T_2'(0) = f'(0)</m> implies <m>c_1 = 1</m>, and <m>T_2''(0) = f''(0)</m> implies <m>2c_2 = 1</m>, so that <m>c_2 = \frac{1}{2}</m>.  Thus, <m>T_2(x) = 1 + x + \frac{1}{2} x^2</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Plotting the function <m>T_2(x) = 1 + x + \frac{1}{2} x^2</m> along with <m>f(x)=e^x</m> and <m>T_1(x)=1+x</m> in <xref ref="F-8a-1-act-1-soln">Figure</xref>, 

						<figure xml:id="F-8a-1-act-1-soln">
							<caption>The function <m>f(x)=e^x</m> and its tangent line <m>T_1(x)=1+x</m> near the point <m>(0,f(0))</m>.</caption>
							<image width="50%" source="images/8a_1_act_1_soln" />
						</figure>
						we notice that <m>T_2(x)</m> is a better approximation to <m>f(x) = e^x</m> near <m>a = 0</m> than the tangent line:  the quadratic approximation is closer to <m>e^x</m> for any value of <m>x</m>, and the approximation holds for a wider interval of values.  For instance, in <xref ref="PA-8a-1">Preview Activity</xref>, we found that <m>|f(x)-T_1(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for approximately <m>-0.5 \lt x \lt 0.4</m>. The quadratica approximation is much better:  we note that <m>|f(x)-T_2(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for approximately <m>-0.9 \lt x \lt 0.8</m>, and for any <m>x</m>-value in that interval, <m>|f(x)-T_2(x)| \lt |f(x)-T_1(x)|</m>. 
					</p>		
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>
			
		</solution>
</activity>

